        <div class="verdict">⭐ Rating: 4.2/5 — Best for mid-size contractors who need deep job costing</div>

        <p>Foundation Software has been building construction-specific accounting software since 1985. That longevity shows — the platform has deep job costing capabilities, construction-specific payroll handling (certified payroll, Davis-Bacon, multi-state workers), and reporting that understands how contractors think about money. It's not the flashiest software in the market, but for mid-size contractors who live and die by their job cost reports, it's one of the most capable platforms available.</p>

        <h2>Who Foundation is designed for</h2>
        <p>Foundation targets mid-size general contractors, specialty subcontractors, and homebuilders in the $2M–$50M revenue range who need serious construction accounting rather than adapted generic accounting software. If QuickBooks is starting to break down for your job costing needs, or if you're running certified payroll manually, Foundation is worth evaluating. It's not right for very small contractors (the price and complexity are overkill) or enterprise GCs (who typically use Sage 300 CRE or Viewpoint Vista).</p>

        <h2>Pricing</h2>
        <p>Foundation doesn't publish pricing publicly, and quotes vary based on company size, modules selected, and deployment method. Expect to budget:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>On-premise:</strong> Upfront license cost (typically $10,000–$30,000+) plus annual maintenance fees</li>
          <li><strong>Cloud (Foundation Cloud):</strong> Monthly subscription pricing; typically $300–$800/month for small to mid-size firms</li>
          <li>Additional costs for payroll, mobile, service dispatch, and other add-on modules</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Contact Foundation directly for accurate current pricing — they will tailor a quote based on your business size and module needs.</p>

        <h2>Core features</h2>

        <h3>Job costing — The standout capability</h3>
        <p>Foundation's job costing is the reason most contractors choose it. You can track costs across detailed cost codes — labor, materials, subcontractors, equipment, overhead — at a granularity that generic accounting tools can't match. Real-time job cost reports show you exactly where every job stands against its budget at any point in the project, not just at closeout.</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Cost code structure:</strong> Set up a cost code hierarchy that matches your bidding structure, then track actuals against it automatically</li>
          <li><strong>Projected cost at completion:</strong> Foundation can project total cost at completion based on actual costs and percentage of work complete</li>
          <li><strong>Over/under billing:</strong> Track WIP (work in progress) with overbilled/underbilled amounts for accurate financial reporting</li>
          <li><strong>Unit cost tracking:</strong> Track costs per unit of work (e.g., cost per square foot, cost per ton) for production-based work</li>
          <li><strong>Equipment cost allocation:</strong> Distribute equipment and rental costs across jobs</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Construction payroll</h3>
        <p>Payroll is one of Foundation's most differentiating features. Construction payroll is genuinely complicated — prevailing wages, certified payroll for government jobs, multiple states, union vs. non-union, multiple jobs per pay period, per diem, and hazard pay. Foundation handles all of this natively, which is rare in mid-market accounting software.</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Certified payroll reports:</strong> Generate WH-347 certified payroll reports for prevailing wage and Davis-Bacon work</li>
          <li><strong>Union fringe benefit tracking:</strong> Calculate and report union benefit contributions per collective bargaining agreement</li>
          <li><strong>Multiple pay rates per employee:</strong> Different rates by job, trade, or work type on the same timecard</li>
          <li><strong>Multi-state payroll:</strong> Handle employees working across state lines with appropriate withholding</li>
          <li><strong>Direct deposit and tax filing</strong></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Accounts payable and receivable</h3>
        <p>Foundation handles the full AP/AR cycle with construction-specific workflows. Subcontractor insurance and lien waiver tracking are built into the AP process — you can require a current certificate of insurance before releasing a payment and track lien waivers against each payment. This is a practical feature that reduces liability exposure and is often not available in generic accounting tools.</p>

        <h3>Project management module</h3>
        <p>Foundation includes project management tools — submittals, RFIs, daily reports, change orders — that are adequate for smaller operations but aren't as robust as dedicated PM platforms like Procore or Buildertrend. If you have complex field coordination needs, you may want to pair Foundation's accounting with a dedicated PM platform.</p>

        <h3>Service dispatch</h3>
        <p>Foundation has a service dispatch module for contractors who also run service operations. It handles work orders, scheduling, and service agreements. It's a reasonable add-on for contractors with a service division, though it's not as capable as purpose-built service platforms like ServiceTitan or Jobber.</p>

        <h2>Pros</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Deep job costing:</strong> One of the most detailed job cost tracking systems in the mid-market</li>
          <li><strong>Construction payroll:</strong> Certified payroll, prevailing wage, union tracking — few competitors match this</li>
          <li><strong>Lien waiver management:</strong> Integrated into AP workflow, reducing manual tracking</li>
          <li><strong>WIP accounting:</strong> Proper work-in-progress reporting for accurate financial statements</li>
          <li><strong>Long track record:</strong> 35+ years in construction accounting; product stability and deep customer support knowledge</li>
          <li><strong>Cloud option available:</strong> Foundation Cloud removes the on-premise IT burden</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Cons</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dated interface:</strong> The UI reflects the platform's age — functional but not modern</li>
          <li><strong>Learning curve:</strong> Significant implementation and training time required; not plug-and-play</li>
          <li><strong>Pricing opacity:</strong> No public pricing; requires a sales conversation to get a quote</li>
          <li><strong>Project management depth:</strong> PM tools are adequate but not best-in-class; heavy PM users may need a second platform</li>
          <li><strong>Limited mobile experience:</strong> Mobile functionality is improving but still behind cloud-native competitors</li>
          <li><strong>Not for small contractors:</strong> Overkill for companies under $2M revenue</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Foundation vs. QuickBooks for contractors</h2>
        <p>The most common upgrade path to Foundation is from QuickBooks. Here's where Foundation wins and where QuickBooks is still adequate:</p>

        <div class="quick-table">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th></th><th>Foundation</th><th>QuickBooks</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Job costing depth</strong></td><td>⭐ Best-in-class</td><td>Basic</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Certified payroll</strong></td><td>⭐ Native</td><td>Third-party add-on needed</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>WIP accounting</strong></td><td>⭐ Built in</td><td>Manual workaround</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Lien waiver tracking</strong></td><td>⭐ Integrated</td><td>Not available</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Setup complexity</strong></td><td>High</td><td>⭐ Low</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Cost</strong></td><td>High</td><td>⭐ Low ($30–$90/mo)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Accountant familiarity</strong></td><td>Specialized</td><td>⭐ Universal</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>When to stay on QuickBooks:</strong> If you're under $2–3M revenue, not doing prevailing wage or union work, and your job costing needs are straightforward, QuickBooks + a construction PM tool is a cost-effective setup that your accountant already knows.</p>

        <p><strong>When to move to Foundation:</strong> When your accountant is spending hours manually building job cost reports, when you're doing certified payroll for government work, when you've lost margin on jobs because you couldn't see cost overruns in real time.</p>

        <h2>Foundation Cloud vs. on-premise</h2>
        <p>Foundation now offers a cloud-hosted version alongside the traditional on-premise deployment. The cloud version removes the need for a server and IT maintenance, and enables browser-based access from any device. For most new Foundation customers, cloud deployment is now the recommended path. Existing on-premise customers can migrate, but the process requires planning and coordination with Foundation's implementation team.</p>

        <h2>Who should use Foundation Software</h2>
        <p><strong>Good fit:</strong> Mid-size GCs, specialty subcontractors, and homebuilders doing $2M–$50M revenue who need serious job costing, certified payroll, and construction-specific WIP accounting. Companies doing prevailing wage or government work will find it especially valuable.</p>
        <p><strong>Not a good fit:</strong> Small contractors under $2M (overkill in price and complexity), very large GCs (who typically need Sage 300 CRE or Viewpoint Vista), or contractors who want a single platform for both accounting and heavy field management (pair Foundation with Procore or Buildertrend instead).</p>

